        contentMd: "# Tracheostomy - Mechanism\n\n## Surgical Technique\n1. Positioning: Supine, neck extended, shoulder roll\n2. Skin incision: Transverse, 2-3 cm, between cricoid and clavicles\n3. Muscle dissection: Strap muscles separated (not cut)\n4. Thyroid management: Isthmus divided or retracted\n5. Tracheal approach: Blunt dissection anterior to trachea\n6. Tracheal entry: Between rings 2-3 (may resect anterior ring cartilage)\n7. Stoma creation: Cruciate or U-flap technique\n8. Tube insertion: Size 8.5-10mm (adult), secured with ties\n\n## Healing Process\nPhase 1 (Minutes-Hours): Bleeding control, hemostasis\nPhase 2 (Days 1-3): Granulation tissue, epithelialization begins\nPhase 3 (Week 1-2): Mature epithelium lines stoma\nPhase 4 (Weeks 2-4): Fibrous tissue formation, tract stabilization\nPhase 5 (Months): Maturation of stoma tract\n\n## Tracheal Changes\n- Loss of ciliary clearance at stoma site\n- Reduced humidification at stoma\n- Epithelial changes: squamous metaplasia\n- Scar tissue formation\n- Potential for stenosis if injury occurs\n\n## Tube-Related Changes\n- Subglottic edema if tube too large\n- Granulation around stoma\n- Tracheomalacia if pressure necrosis\n- Tracheal stenosis (late, rare)\n\n## Physiological Impact\n- Airway resistance ↓ (shorter path)\n- Work of breathing ↓\n- Tidal volumes may increase\n- Functional residual capacity may change\n- Aspiration risk ↓ (glottis bypassed)\n- Phonation requires valving or cap",
