        contentMd: "# Tracheostomy - Clinical\n\n## Indications (Common)\n1. Prolonged mechanical ventilation (>10-14 days)\n2. Difficult or failed intubation\n3. Airway protection (unconscious, aspiration risk)\n4. Obstructive sleep apnea (severe)\n5. Laryngeal paralysis, stenosis\n6. Tumors of larynx, pharynx (temporary or permanent)\n7. Trauma: Laryngeal injury, severe facial trauma\n8. Post-surgical airway (laryngectomy)\n\n## Relative Indications\n- Chronic aspiration\n- Severe COPD with ventilatory failure\n- Neuromuscular disease\n- Severe obstructive pathology\n\n## Indian Clinical Context\n- Limited ICU beds: Tracheostomy allows early ICU discharge\n- Post-polio syndrome: Chronic ventilation support\n- Severe tobacco use: COPD, laryngeal cancer\n- Aspiration common in stroke, neurologic disease\n- Rural areas: Delayed care increases severity\n\n## Acute Complications (0-24 hours)\n- Hemorrhage: From vessel injury, can be life-threatening\n- Tube misplacement: Subcutaneous, into false tract\n- Tube obstruction: Clot, mucus, fibrin\n- Hypoxia: From tube dislodgment\n- Subcutaneous emphysema: Air tracking into soft tissues\n\n## Early Complications (Days 1-7)\n- Infection: Cellulitis, mediastinitis\n- Tube blockage: Secretion plugging\n- Tracheal stenosis: Pressure necrosis beginning\n- Aspiration: If cuff inadequate\n- Accidental decannulation: Tube falls out\n\n## Late Complications (Weeks-Months)\n- Tracheal stenosis: Scarring, 1-2% rate\n- Tracheomalacia: Cartilage weakening\n- Tracheo-innominate fistula: RARE, FATAL if occurs\n- Granulation tissue\n- Persistent stoma: Won't close after decannulation\n- Swallowing dysfunction\n- Aspiration pneumonia\n\n## Clinical Assessment\nDaily checks:\n- Tube position, patency\n- Cuff pressure (20-25 cmH2O)\n- Skin around stoma: Signs of infection\n- Secretion character\n- Respiration: Rate, effort, SpO2\n- Speaking valve tolerance\n- Swallowing status\n\n## Decannulation\nWhen ready: Tube can be removed, stoma typically closes within days-weeks (rarely persists).\nAssess: No longer needs airway protection/ventilation, intact swallowing, adequate cough.",
