        summary: "Management protocols, tube types, troubleshooting, and when to refer.",
        contentMd: "# Tracheostomy - Exam Prep\n\n## Tube Types\n1. Cuffed tubes: Seal airway, prevent aspiration\n   - Allow mechanical ventilation\n   - Require cuff pressure monitoring\n   - Adult sizes 8.5-10 mm\n\n2. Uncuffed tubes: For breathing only\n   - Allow better phonation\n   - Higher aspiration risk\n   - Used after initial healing\n\n3. Fenestrated tubes: Opening in anterior wall\n   - Allow air through vocal cords (phonation)\n   - Must plug cap for ventilation\n   - Risk: Tracheal granulation at fenestra\n\n4. Speaking valves: One-way valves\n   - Allow speech during exhalation\n   - Only with cuffed tubes\n   - Improve quality of life\n\n## Cuff Management\n1. Cuff pressure: 20-25 cmH2O ideal\n2. Over-inflation: Tracheal ischemia → stenosis\n3. Under-inflation: Aspiration, air leak\n4. Monitoring: Cuff pressure manometer\n5. Minimal leak technique: Just enough pressure for seal\n\n## Tube Plugging Protocol (Weaning)\nDay 1-2: On mechanical ventilation, cuffed\nDay 3-7: Day hours plug trial (if breathing adequate)\nDay 7-14: Longer plug trials, assess swallowing\nDay 14+: Decannulation if ready\n\n## Emergency: Tube Obstruction\n1. Assess: Breathing difficulty, high airway pressures\n2. Suction: Gently insert suction catheter\n3. Instill saline: 2-3 mL to loosen secretions\n4. Suction again\n5. If unresolved: Tube change\n6. Spare tube should be at bedside\n\n## Emergency: Accidental Decannulation\n1. Stay calm, reassure patient\n2. Head-of-bed up to 30 degrees\n3. Visualize stoma\n4. Try to reinsert tube (may go into false tract)\n5. If unsuccessful: Bag-mask ventilation\n6. Call for assistance\n7. May need endoscopy if unable to reinsert\n\n## Tube Change Protocol\n- First change: Day 7-10 (tract mature enough)\n- Routine: Every 4-8 weeks\n- Procedure: Have spare tube, suction ready\n- Size same or smaller\n- Cuff pressure check post-change\n\n## Tracheal Stenosis Prevention\n1. Optimal cuff pressure (20-25 cmH2O)\n2. Avoid over-sized tubes\n3. Regular tube changes\n4. Avoid prolonged cuff inflation\n5. Maintain cuff integrity\n6. Early detection: Stridor on decannulation\n\n## Tracheo-Innominate Fistula (RARE)\nSigns: Massive hemorrhage (200-400 mL), pulsatile bleeding from stoma\nManagement: EMERGENCY\n- Inflate cuff maximally (tamponade)\n- 100% O2\n- IV access, blood typed\n- Emergent surgical exploration\n- Mortality: 50% even with treatment\n\n## Decannulation Decision\nCriteria:\n- Stable respiratory status off ventilation\n- Adequate swallowing\n- Cough strong enough to clear secretions\n- No active infection\n- Cuff down, tolerates plugging\n- Alert, cooperative\n\nProcess:\n- Downsize tube if possible\n- Plug trials 4-6 hours daily\n- Extend plugging time\n- Remove tube when ready\n- Stoma care with sterile dressing\n- Usually closes within 1-2 weeks\n\n## Speaking Valve Introduction\n1. Used during daytime only initially\n2. Remove at night for sleeping\n3. Must have cuffed tube\n4. Facilitates phonation\n5. Reduces social isolation\n6. Improves quality of life",
