        estimatedMinutes: 15,
        summary: "Critical facts, complications, and clinical pearls for rapid recall.",
        contentMd: "# Tracheostomy - Active Recall\n\n## MUST KNOW Facts\n1. Level: 2nd-3rd tracheal ring (standardization)\n2. Technique: Transverse incision, separate strap muscles, don't cut them\n3. Cuff pressure: 20-25 cmH2O (prevent stenosis)\n4. First change: Day 7-10 (tract mature)\n5. Decannulation: When breathing adequate, swallowing intact\n6. Stoma closure: 1-2 weeks post-decannulation (usually)\n\n## Complications: Acute vs Late\nACUTE (0-24h): Bleeding, tube misplacement, obstruction, emphysema\nEARLY (1-7d): Infection, blockage, stenosis beginning\nLATE (weeks+): Stenosis, tracheomalacia, fistula\n\n## Emergency: Tracheo-Innominate Fistula\n- Massive hemorrhage 200-400 mL\n- Pulsatile bleeding\n- Inflate cuff (tamponade)\n- Emergent surgery\n- 50% mortality\n\n## Emergency: Tube Obstruction\n- Suction: Catheter past obstruction\n- Saline: Loosen secretions\n- Change: If unresolved\n- Spare tube at bedside mandatory\n\n## Emergency: Accidental Decannulation\n- Don't panic, reassure patient\n- Try reinsert (watch false tract)\n- Bag-mask ventilation if fails\n- May need endoscopy\n- Rare after tract matures (>7 days)\n\n## Tube Plugging Sequence\nDay 1-2: Mechanical ventilation, cuffed\nDay 3-7: Daytime plugging trials\nDay 7-14: Longer plugging\nDay 14+: Decannulation if criteria met\n\n## Decannulation Criteria\n1. Off mechanical ventilation (or minimal support)\n2. Adequate swallowing (cuff down tolerates)\n3. Strong cough\n4. Alert, cooperative\n5. No active infection\n6. Adequate oxygenation\n\n## Stenosis Prevention\n- Optimal cuff pressure (20-25)\n- Appropriately sized tube\n- Regular tube changes\n- Avoid over-inflation\n- Maintain cuff integrity\n\n## Speaking Valve Pearl\n- Only with cuffed tube\n- One-way valve\n- Air enters through nose/mouth\n- Exits around tube into voicebox\n- Improves quality of life dramatically\n- Remove at night\n\n## Exam Differentials\n- Endotracheal tube: Temporary, laryngeal trauma risk\n- Cricothyrotomy: Emergency only, not for prolonged use\n- Laryngectomy: Permanent, for laryngeal cancer\n- Tracheal stenosis: Complication of tracheostomy\n\n## Indian Context Pearl\n- Tracheostomy allows ICU bed turnover\n- Common: Post-polio, COPD, stroke aspiration\n- Home care: Family should be trained\n- Funding: Often government-sponsored\n- Rehabilitation: Earlier discharge possible\n\n## Clinical Pearls\n- Mark tracheal ring level during first tube change\n- Humidification important to prevent tube occlusion\n- Suctioning technique: Gentle, <10 seconds\n- Monitor cuff pressure twice daily\n- Speaking valve transforms social engagement\n- Stoma should NOT require dressing after healing\n- Decannulation rates 80-90% successful in ICU",
