        summary: "Basic types of hearing aids and cochlear implants, their indications and mechanisms.",
        contentMd: "# Hearing Aids & Cochlear Implants - Foundation\n\n## Hearing Aids: Types\n1. Behind-the-Ear (BTE): Most common, powerful, versatile\n2. In-the-Ear (ITE): Smaller, visible, moderate power\n3. In-the-Canal (ITC): Highly discreet, limited power\n4. Completely-in-Canal (CIC): Invisible, very limited power\n\n## Hearing Aid Components\n- Microphone: Picks up sound\n- Amplifier: Increases volume\n- Receiver: Converts electrical signal to sound\n- Battery: Powers the device\n- Earmold: Carries sound to ear canal (BTE)\n\n## How Hearing Aids Work\n1. Microphone captures sound\n2. Analog or digital signal processing\n3. Amplification of selected frequencies\n4. Receiver plays amplified sound in ear\n5. Uses natural ear canal conduction\n\n## Cochlear Implants: Overview\nElectronic device for severe-profound bilateral sensorineural hearing loss:\n- External processor: Microphone, sound processor\n- Internal implant: Electrode array in cochlea\n- Stimulates auditory nerve directly\n- Not for conductive hearing loss\n\n## Indications for Devices\nHearing Aids: Mild to severe sensorineural hearing loss, functional hearing thresholds\n\nCochlear Implants: Severe-profound bilateral SNHL, inadequate benefit from hearing aids",
