        estimatedMinutes: 15,
        summary: "Critical facts, decision algorithms, and clinical pearls.",
        contentMd: "# Hearing Aids & Cochlear Implants - Active Recall\n\n## MUST KNOW Facts\n1. HA: Mild-severe SNHL, amplifies via earmold\n2. CI: Severe-profound SNHL, failed HA trial\n3. CI indications: Bilateral, adequate CN VIII function\n4. HA types: BTE (powerful), CIC (discreet, weak)\n5. CI outcome: 50-80% open-set speech recognition\n6. Meningitis risk CI: 10-30x population, vaccination needed\n\n## Device Selection Algorithm\nStep 1: Determine hearing loss degree\nStep 2: Test speech discrimination\nStep 3: If mild-severe + good discrimination → Hearing aid\nStep 4: If severe-profound + poor HA benefit → CI evaluation\nStep 5: Pre-CI imaging + ABR assessment\nStep 6: Surgical implantation if candidate\nStep 7: Activation + programming + rehabilitation\n\n## Hearing Aid Fitting Essentials\n- Audiometry first (degree, frequencies, discrimination)\n- Earmold impression\n- Gain prescription (DSL, NAL-NL2)\n- Real-ear measurement verification\n- Trial period 2-4 weeks\n- Adjustments based on feedback\n\n## HA Feedback Problem\n- Cause: Amplified sound re-enters microphone\n- Solutions: Better fit, phase cancellation, algorithms\n- Prevention: Proper earmold fit\n\n## CI Candidate Must-Haves\n1. Severe-profound bilateral SNHL\n2. Failed adequate trial of hearing aids\n3. CN VIII functional (imaging, testing)\n4. Realistic expectations\n5. Motivation for rehabilitation\n6. Medical clearance for surgery\n\n## Pre-CI Imaging Red Flags\n- Cochlear ossification (post-meningitis)\n- Acoustic neuroma (CN VIII compromise)\n- Malformation (lacks normal anatomy)\n- Temporal bone fracture (ototoxic?\n- Labyrinthitis ossificans (post-labyrinthitis)\n\n## CI Activation Timeline\nWeek 2-4: First activation, impedance check, initial mapping\nWeek 4-8: Programming adjustments, acclimatization\nMonth 2-6: Intensive aural rehabilitation\nMonth 6+: Plateau function (50-80% sentences)\n\n## CI Outcomes Determinants\n1. Age at implantation: Congenital < acquired\n2. Deafness duration: Shorter = better\n3. Pre-CI speech discrimination: Better = better\n4. Rehabilitation adherence: Critical\n5. Expectations: Realistic > unrealistic\n\n## Meningitis Prevention Post-CI\n- PCV13 vaccine before implantation\n- PPSV23 booster if needed\n- Patient education: Fever signs\n- Emergency access: Know when to seek help\n\n## HA vs CI Decision Matrix\nMild-Moderate SNHL: Hearing aid\nSevere SNHL, good discrimination: Hearing aid trial\nSevere SNHL, poor discrimination: CI consideration\nProfound SNHL, failed HA: CI indicated\n\n## Red Flags Post-CI\n- High fever + stiff neck: Meningitis emergency\n- CSF clear drainage: CSF leak, needs repair\n- Device not activating: Magnet check, radiography\n- Complete feedback/no output: Electrode issue, reprogramming\n\n## Clinical Pearls\n- Real-ear measurement: Ensures proper HA fit\n- Earmold impression quality: Critical for HA success\n- Trial period patience: 2-4 weeks for adaptation\n- CI rehabilitation: Most important factor post-implantation\n- Device loyalty: Most patients wear same brand HA long-term\n- CI speech perception: Improves over 1-2 years\n- Bilateral CI: Better for sound localization, music\n- Single CI: Adequate for phone, conversation\n\n## Exam Differentials\n- Sudden SNHL: Medical emergency, steroids before device\n- Conductive loss: Correct surgically before HA\n- Central auditory processing disorder: HA may not help speech\n- Dementia: HA benefit limited, behavioral changes\n- Acoustic neuroma: CI contraindicated\n\n## India-Specific Issues\n- Cost: Major barrier, seek government schemes\n- Access: Limited CI centers, concentration in metros\n- Awareness: Health education needed\n- Rehabilitation: Inadequate post-CI support\n- Stigma: Delay in seeking help\n- Follow-up: Compliance poor, need incentive programs",
