        summary: "Anatomy of venous system and mechanisms of varicose vein development.",
        contentMd: "# Varicose Veins - Foundation\n\n## Venous System Overview\nDeep veins: Inside muscle compartments, carry 90% of blood\nSuperficial veins: Under skin, saphenous veins main\nCommunicating veins: Connect deep to superficial\nValves: Prevent backflow, more in legs (gravity effect)\n\n## Normal Venous Return\n- Muscle pump: Calf, thigh muscles push blood upward\n- Valve function: Prevents retrograde flow\n- Respiratory pump: Diaphragm assists venous return\n- Intramural pressure gradient\n\n## Varicose Veins Definition\nAbnormally dilated, tortuous superficial veins with valve incompetence.\nDiameter >3 mm considered pathological.\n\n## Main Sites\n1. Greater saphenous vein (80%): Medial leg\n2. Lesser saphenous vein (20%): Lateral leg\n3. Tributary veins\n\n## Classification\nPrimary (80-90%): Weak venous walls, valve insufficiency\nSecondary (10-20%): Following DVT, post-thrombotic syndrome",
