        title: "Varicose Veins - Mechanism",
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        summary: "Pathophysiology of valve failure and venous wall changes.",
        contentMd: "# Varicose Veins - Mechanism\n\n## Primary Pathophysiology\nVenous Wall Degenerative Changes:\n- Loss of elastic fibers\n- Smooth muscle atrophy\n- Collagen increase, abnormal distribution\n- Weakened wall structure\n\nValve Failure:\n- Valve cusps stretch (dilated vein)\n- Leaflets fail to coapt\n- Vein dilation > 2 mm causes leaflet coaptation failure\n- Reflux develops\n\n## Secondary Pathophysiology\nPost-Thrombotic Syndrome:\n- DVT damages valve function\n- Obstruction causes venous hypertension\n- Venous dilation develops\n- Incompetent valves result\n- Chronic venous insufficiency follows\n\n## Hemodynamic Consequences\n1. Increased venous pressure (hydrostatic)\n2. Venous hypertension in superficial system\n3. Capillary dilation, increased filtration\n4. Fluid extravasation into tissues\n5. Edema develops\n6. White blood cell trapping, inflammation\n7. Skin changes (pigmentation, ulceration)\n\n## Incompetence Severity Grading\nClass C1: Telangiectasias (<3mm)\nClass C2: Varicose veins (>3mm)\nClass C3: Edema\nClass C4: Skin pigment changes, eczema\nClass C5: Healed ulcer\nClass C6: Active ulcer\n\n## Risk Factors for Development\n- Genetic predisposition (family history)\n- Female gender (3:1 ratio)\n- Prolonged standing\n- Pregnancy (hormonal, mechanical)\n- Age (>40 common)\n- Obesity (increased pressure)\n- Sedentary lifestyle",
