        slug: "varicose-veins-clinical",
        title: "Varicose Veins - Clinical",
        estimatedMinutes: 25,
        summary: "Clinical presentation, diagnosis, and Indian context management.",
        contentMd: "# Varicose Veins - Clinical\n\n## Clinical Presentation\nAsymptomatic:\n- Cosmetic concern (many cases)\n- Visible leg veins, tortuous\n- May have no symptoms\n\nSymptomaticPresentation:\n- Heaviness, aching legs\n- Fatigue (evening worse)\n- Itching, burning sensation\n- Leg swelling (evening worse, morning improves)\n- Cramps, especially at night\n- Pain with standing\n\n## Complications\nAcute Thrombophlebitis:\n- Tender, red varicose segment\n- Localized pain\n- Inflammation along vein\n- Usually superficial (70%), rarely extends to deep\n\nVenous Ulceration:\n- Usually medial ankle (gaiter distribution)\n- Difficult to heal\n- Recurrent without treatment\n- Often in advanced CVI (C5-C6)\n\nBleeding:\n- Rupture of varicose vein\n- Usually minor, self-limiting\n- Can be problematic in anticoagulated patients\n\nStasis Dermatitis:\n- Skin discoloration, pigmentation changes\n- Dry, itchy skin\n- Eczema-like appearance\n\n## Physical Examination\nInspection:\n- Standing position: Note dilated veins\n- Bilateral assessment\n- Skin changes: Pigmentation, scars, ulcers\n- Asymmetry (unilateral prominent)\n\nPalpation:\n- Vein compressibility\n- Warmth, tenderness (inflammation?)\n- Edema grade\n- Skin induration, ulcers\n\nSpecial Tests:\n- Trendelenburg test: Competence of saphenofemoral junction\n- Perthes test: Patent deep veins\n- Tourniquet test: Vein source localization\n- Tap impulse: Vein continuity\n\n## Differential Diagnosis\n- Spider veins (telangiectasias): <1mm, benign\n- Restless leg syndrome: Neurologic, no visible veins\n- Cellulitis: Acute inflammation, fever\n- DVT: Swelling, pain, risk factors\n- Lymphedema: Bilateral, harder, pitting less\n\n## Indian Context\n- High prevalence in urban population (sitting jobs)\n- Hot climate: Increased symptoms\n- Limited specialist access: Rural areas\n- Economic constraint: Affects treatment access\n- Occupational: Long-standing workers (shops, factories)\n- Pregnancy-related: Common in young women",
