        estimatedMinutes: 20,
        summary: "Investigations, treatment options, and management algorithms.",
        contentMd: "# Varicose Veins - Exam Prep\n\n## Investigations\nClinical Examination: Often sufficient for uncomplicated VV\n\nDuplex Ultrasound:\n- Gold standard for diagnosis\n- Assesses valve function (reflux presence)\n- Identifies source of reflux\n- Evaluates patency of deep veins\n- Guides treatment planning\n\nTreatment Algorithm:\n\nAsymptomatic, No Complications:\n- Observation, compression stockings if desired\n- No intervention needed\n- Annual assessment\n\nSymptomaticWith Complications or Patient Request:\n1. Conservative Management (First-line):\n   - Leg elevation\n   - Compression stockings (Class 1-3)\n   - Regular exercise\n   - Weight management\n   - Avoid prolonged standing\n   - Duration: 3-6 months trial\n\n2. Minimally Invasive (If conservative fails or complications):\n   a) Endovenous Laser Ablation (EVLA):\n      - Heat vein wall → thrombosis\n      - Excellent success rate (95%)\n      - Outpatient procedure\n      - Minimal pain\n      - Can treat under local anesthesia\n      - Recovery: 1-2 weeks\n\n   b) Radiofrequency Ablation (RFA):\n      - Similar to EVLA\n      - Radiofrequency energy\n      - Excellent outcomes\n      - Slightly better for larger veins\n\n   c) Sclerotherapy:\n      - Chemical injection into vein\n      - Causes inflammation → thrombosis\n      - Good for smaller veins, tributaries\n      - Multiple sessions often needed\n      - Cheaper option\n\n   d) Foam Sclerotherapy:\n      - Sclerosant mixed with air\n      - Better penetration\n      - For larger veins\n      - Requires ultrasound guidance\n\n3. Surgical (Open Surgery):\n   - Vein stripping: Removal of GSV\n   - Usually reserved for:\n      - Failed minimally invasive\n      - Extensive disease\n      - Recurrent VV\n   - High success rate but more morbidity\n   - Bruising, pain, longer recovery (2-4 weeks)\n   - Nerve injury risk (saphenous)\n\n## Treatment Selection in India\nContext:\n- Cost: Conservative > sclerotherapy > ablation > surgery\n- Access: Urban has ablation, rural lacks specialists\n- Insurance: Often not covered\n- Patient factors: Education, expectations\n\nCommon Indian Approach:\n1. Conservative first (leg elevation, compression)\n2. Sclerotherapy if fails (cheaper than ablation)\n3. EVLA if complications (better outcomes)\n4. Surgery rarely offered (cost, expertise)\n\n## Compression Stocking Therapy\nClass 1: 15-20 mmHg (mild, prevention)\nClass 2: 20-30 mmHg (moderate, symptomatic)\nClass 3: 30-40 mmHg (severe, venous insufficiency)\n\nUsage: Full-length preferred, at least knee-high\nTiming: Morning put on, remove evening\nDuration: Daily for symptom relief\n\n## Post-Treatment Follow-up\nAfter Ablation/Sclerotherapy:\n- Compression stockings 1-2 weeks\n- Leg elevation\n- Walking encouraged\n- No strenuous exercise (2 weeks)\n- Return to work: 1-2 days\n\nComplications to Monitor:\n- Thrombophlebitis: Tender, inflamed segment\n- DVT: Calf swelling, pain (urgent duplex)\n- Skin burn: Heat injury\n- Nerve injury: Numbness (saphenous)\n\n## Recurrence Rates\n- EVLA/RFA: 10-15% at 5 years\n- Sclerotherapy: 40-60% at 5 years\n- Surgery: 20-40% at 5 years (neovascularization)\n- GSV reflux elimination required to prevent recurrence",
