        estimatedMinutes: 15,
        summary: "Critical facts, treatment decision logic, and clinical pearls.",
        contentMd: "# Varicose Veins - Active Recall\n\n## MUST KNOW Facts\n1. VV: Dilated superficial veins >3mm\n2. GSV: 80% cases, medial leg\n3. Pathophysiology: Valve incompetence + venous hypertension\n4. Conservative: Elevation, compression, exercise\n5. EVLA: Best minimally invasive (95% success)\n6. Sclerotherapy: Cheaper, good for small veins\n7. Surgery: Last resort, higher morbidity\n\n## Treatment Algorithm\nAsymptomatic → Observation only\nSymptomaticWithout Complications → Conservative 3-6 months\nFailed Conservative OR Complications → Consider Ablation/Sclerotherapy\nExtensive or Recurrent → Surgery\n\n## Conservative Management\n- Leg elevation: Most important\n- Compression stockings: Class 2-3\n- Regular exercise: Walking\n- Weight management\n- Avoid prolonged standing\n- Trial period: 3-6 months\n\n## Minimally Invasive Techniques\nEVLA (Endovenous Laser):\n- 95% success, outpatient\n- Local anesthesia\n- 1-2 weeks recovery\n- Cost: Moderate-high\n\nSclerotherapy:\n- Inject chemical\n- Good for tributaries\n- Multiple sessions needed\n- Cheaper\n- 40-60% recurrence\n\n## Complications Recognition\nThrombophlebitis: Tender, red, localized inflammation\nDVT: Calf swelling, pain (requires urgent duplex)\nUlcers: Medial ankle, difficult to heal\nBleeding: Rupture, usually self-limited\n\n## Compression Stocking Use\n- Class 2: 20-30 mmHg (symptomatic)\n- Class 3: 30-40 mmHg (venous insufficiency)\n- Put on morning, remove evening\n- Daily wear\n- Essential post-treatment\n\n## Duplex Ultrasound\n- Confirms diagnosis\n- Assesses valve competence\n- Evaluates deep vein patency\n- Guides treatment\n- No contraindications\n\n## Recurrence Rates\n- EVLA: 10-15% (best)\n- Surgery: 20-40% (neovascularization)\n- Sclerotherapy: 40-60% (worst)\n- Related to: Reflux persistence, inadequate treatment\n\n## Post-Treatment Instructions\n- Compression: 1-2 weeks minimum\n- Walking: Encouraged\n- Elevation: Frequent\n- No strenuous exercise: 2 weeks\n- Return to work: 1-2 days\n\n## Red Flags\n- Sudden swelling: Possible DVT\n- Warmth, redness beyond treated vein: Cellulitis\n- Severe pain: Thrombophlebitis\n- Fever: Infection\n- High output bleeding: Rupture (apply pressure)\n\n## Exam Pearls\n- 80% symptomatic VV asymptomatic\n- Cosmetic concern drives many treatments\n- CEAP classification: C1-C6 severity\n- GSV saphenofemoral junction (SFJ) most common source\n- Trendelenburg test: Checks SFJ competence\n- Perthes test: Assesses deep vein patency\n- Night cramps: Common symptom\n- Restless leg syndrome: Must differentiate (no visible veins)\n\n## India-Specific Approach\n- Cost: Major limiting factor\n- Urban: EVLA available\n- Rural: Conservative, sclerotherapy only options\n- Awareness: Low, late presentation\n- Occupational: Long-standing workers affected\n- Pregnancy: Common trigger in young women\n\n## Differential Diagnosis\n- Spider veins: Cosmetic, benign (<3mm)\n- Cellulitis: Acute, fever, tender area\n- DVT: Calf swelling, risk factors, urgent duplex\n- Lymphedema: Bilateral possible, harder, pitting less\n- Arthritis: Joint swelling, pain with movement\n\n## Prognosis\n- Conservative: 30-40% improvement with therapy\n- EVLA: 85-95% success, excellent symptom relief\n- Sclerotherapy: 60-80% success, high recurrence\n- Surgery: 90% success, higher complications\n- Untreated: Potential for ulceration (C5-C6)",
