        contentMd: "# DVT & Peripheral Arterial Disease - Mechanism\n\n## DVT Pathophysiology\nCoagulation Cascade Activation:\n1. Endothelial injury → Tissue factor exposed\n2. Extrinsic pathway: TF + Factor VII → TF-VIIa complex\n3. Thrombin generation: Factor IIa\n4. Fibrin formation: Fibrinogen → Fibrin\n5. Platelet activation and aggregation\n6. Clot propagation\n\nStasis Mechanism:\n- Venous return ↓ (immobility, surgery, cardiac disease)\n- Blood velocity ↓\n- Rheology changes\n- Venous valves may trap blood\n- Clot formation favored\n\nHemodynamic Consequence:\n- Venous obstruction\n- Pressure ↑ distal\n- Edema formation\n- Pain from swelling\n- Risk of pulmonary embolism if thrombus embolizes\n\n## PAD Pathophysiology\nAtherosclerosis Development:\n1. Endothelial injury (smoking, hypertension, hyperlipidemia)\n2. LDL accumulation in intima\n3. Oxidized LDL uptake by macrophages\n4. Foam cell formation\n5. Smooth muscle proliferation\n6. Fibrous cap formation\n7. Lipid core accumulation\n8. Plaque rupture risk\n9. Thrombosis superimposed\n\nArterial Narrowing Progression:\n- Stenosis develops gradually\n- >50% narrowing: Flow reduction starts\n- >70% narrowing: Significant flow reduction\n- >90% narrowing: Critical stenosis\n- Collateral circulation: May compensate for gradual narrowing\n\n## Ischemic Cascade\n1. Blood flow ↓\n2. Oxygen delivery ↓\n3. Aerobic metabolism → Anaerobic\n4. Lactate production ↑\n5. Tissue pH ↓\n6. Muscle pain (claudication)\n7. Rest → oxygen restoration → pain relief\n8. Critical ischemia: Constant pain at rest\n\n## Acute vs Chronic\nAcute DVT: Hours-days, sudden thrombosis\nChronic DVT: Post-thrombotic syndrome, valve damage\n\nAcute PAD: Arterial occlusion, embolism (6 P's: Pain, Pallor, Pulselessness, Paresthesia, Paralysis, Perishing)\nChronic PAD: Gradual stenosis, collateral development, claudication",
