        contentMd: "# DVT & Peripheral Arterial Disease - Clinical\n\n## DVT Clinical Presentation\nSymptoms:\n- Unilateral leg swelling (>2cm difference)\n- Calf pain, tenderness\n- Warmth over vein\n- Heaviness, fatigue\n- May be asymptomatic\n\nSigns:\n- Edema (soft, pitting)\n- Erythema over vein\n- Warmth, cord-like vein palpable\n- Homan's sign: Calf pain on dorsiflexion (low sensitivity)\n- Wells score: Predicts DVT probability\n\nDifferential Diagnosis:\n- Cellulitis: Diffuse, fever, unclear borders\n- Muscle strain: Localized, traumatic history\n- Lymphedema: Gradual onset, bilateral possible, hard\n- Baker's cyst rupture: Behind knee pain\n\n## PAD Clinical Presentation\nIntermittent Claudication:\n- Reproducible muscle pain with activity\n- Location: Calf (femoropopliteal), buttock (iliac)\n- Relieves within 10 minutes rest\n- Severity stable (chronic)\n- Predictable distance\n\nCritical Limb Ischemia:\n- Rest pain: Night pain, foot elevation worsens\n- Non-healing ulcers\n- Gangrene, blackening toes/feet\n- Severe disability\n- Amputation risk\n\nExamination Findings:\n- Pulse assessment: Femoral, popliteal, dorsalis pedis, posterior tibial\n- Absent pulses suggest proximal disease\n- Bruit: Turbulent flow suggests stenosis\n- Pallor on elevation, rubor on dependency\n- Skin: Atrophic, shiny, hairless\n- Temperature: Cool limb\n- Ulcers or gangrene\n- Toenail dystrophy\n\n## Indian Context DVT\n- Higher thrombophilia in South Asian populations (genetic)\n- Immobility: Long-distance travel, tight economy class\n- Malignancy: Advanced cancers more common in late diagnosis\n- Surgical: More elective surgeries without prophylaxis\n- Cost: Anticoagulation therapy expensive\n\n## Indian Context PAD\n- Smoking: Very high prevalence\n- Diabetes: Major epidemic in India\n- Rural prevalence: Higher, late diagnosis\n- Access: Limited vascular specialists in non-metro areas\n- Critical limb ischemia: Often leads to amputation",
