        contentMd: "# DVT & Peripheral Arterial Disease - Active Recall\n\n## MUST KNOW Facts DVT\n1. Virchow's triad: Stasis, vein injury, hypercoagulability\n2. Imaging: Duplex ultrasound gold standard\n3. Treatment: Anticoagulation essential (heparin then warfarin/DOAC)\n4. Duration: 3 months (provoked), 6-12+ months (unprovoked)\n5. PE risk: Proximal DVT > distal\n6. Post-thrombotic syndrome: 30-50% develop chronic symptoms\n\n## MUST KNOW Facts PAD\n1. Claudication: Reproducible pain with exercise, relief at rest\n2. ABI: First-line, <0.9 diagnostic\n3. Critical limb ischemia: Rest pain, ulcers, gangrene\n4. Management: Exercise, smoking cessation, revascularization\n5. Smoking: Most important modifiable risk\n6. Diabetes: Major risk factor\n\n## DVT Risk Factors Mnemonic\nImmonility: Surgery, bed rest, paralysis, long flights\nMalignancy: Hypercoagulable state\nObesity, Oral contraceptives\nBility: Surgical procedures\n\nDVT Assessment:\n- Unilateral leg swelling\n- Calf pain, tenderness\n- Warmth over vein\n- Wells score: Calculate probability\n\n## PAD Stages (Fontaine)\nStage I: Asymptomatic narrowing\nStage II: Claudication (IIa mild, IIb severe)\nStage III: Rest pain\nStage IV: Tissue loss (ulcer, gangrene)\n\n## Anticoagulation Choices for DVT\nUnfractionated Heparin (UFH):\n- Reversible with protamine\n- Rapid onset (minutes)\n- Renal adjustment not needed\n- Cost: Moderate\n- Requires ICU monitoring\n\nLow-Molecular-Weight Heparin (LMWH):\n- Subcutaneous dosing\n- Weight-based\n- Predictable kinetics\n- Cost: Moderate\n- Renal impairment: Caution\n\nWarfarin:\n- Oral\n- Cost: Very cheap\n- INR monitoring: Required\n- Food interactions\n- Drug interactions: Many\n- Slow onset (days)\n\nDOAC (Apixaban, Rivaroxaban):\n- Oral\n- Fixed dose\n- No monitoring\n- Cost: High\n- Renal impairment: Caution\n- Contraindicated in pregnancy\n\n## PAD Exercise Program\n- Supervised walking: Essential\n- Duration: 30+ minutes\n- Frequency: 3x per week minimum\n- Progression: Gradual increase\n- Symptom: Walk to pain, rest to relief\n- Expected: 50% improvement in claudication distance\n\n## Emergency Recognition DVT\n- Massive PE: Sudden dyspnea, chest pain, syncope\n- Phlegmasia cerulea dolens: Severe swelling, cyanosis, pain (venous gangrene)\n- Treatment: Urgent thrombolysis or thrombectomy\n\n## Emergency Recognition PAD\n- Acute limb ischemia: Sudden pain, pallor, pulselessness\n- 6 Ps: Pain, Pallor, Pulselessness, Paresthesia, Paralysis, Perishing\n- Treatment: Urgent revascularization (within 6-8 hours)\n- Contrast CT angiography for diagnosis\n\n## Red Flags\nDVT:\n- Bilateral leg swelling: IVC thrombosis suspect\n- Sudden dyspnea: PE suspect\n- Chest pain: PE suspect\n\nPAD:\n- Sudden pain increase: Acute occlusion suspect\n- Toes blackening: Gangrene development\n- Foot coldness: Critical ischemia\n\n## Clinical Pearls\n- DVT asymptomatic in 20-30% of cases\n- PAD patients have systemic atherosclerosis\n- MI/stroke risk in PAD: Screen for coronary, cerebrovascular disease\n- Post-thrombotic syndrome: Compression stockings help\n- Exercise program: Best medical therapy for PAD\n- Endovascular first: Preferred over open surgery when feasible\n- Smoking cessation: Single best intervention for PAD\n\n## Exam Strategy\n- DVT: Duplex → Anticoagulate\n- PAD: ABI → Conservative (exercise, smoking cessation)\n- If conservative fails or critical: Intervention\n- Always assess other arterial territories (coronary, carotid)\n\n## India-Specific Considerations\n- Cost of anticoagulation: Major issue\n- Warfarin: Limited INR monitoring access\n- Endovascular: Urban metros only\n- Amputation rates: High due to late presentation\n- Diabetes: Drives PAD prevalence\n- Smoking: Major risk in males",
